WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.970 --> 00:00:04.680
MALE SPEAKER: Welcome everyone.

00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:08.840
Anyone who has read "An Annual
Letter of Berkshire Hathaway"

00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:12.620
has often come away marveling
at Warren Buffett's ability

00:00:12.620 --> 00:00:20.130
to distill complex concepts
into very intuitive language.

00:00:20.130 --> 00:00:24.560
Our speaker for
today, Mohnish Pabrai,

00:00:24.560 --> 00:00:27.940
is someone who paid
$650,000 for a lunch

00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:30.860
with Warren Buffett in 2007.

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:33.620
It's a sum he calls a bargain.

00:00:33.620 --> 00:00:37.570
And in the same spirit as Warren
Buffett and Charlie Munger,

00:00:37.570 --> 00:00:42.070
he has a very intuitive, very
evocative, very emotionally

00:00:42.070 --> 00:00:46.710
appealing way of
distilling complex concepts

00:00:46.710 --> 00:00:50.700
into his form of connecting
with the audience.

00:00:50.700 --> 00:00:53.860
He is probably a
fantastic teacher,

00:00:53.860 --> 00:00:57.070
although he does not
carry that official title,

00:00:57.070 --> 00:00:59.500
if you go by any of
his presentations

00:00:59.500 --> 00:01:02.780
to various university groups.

00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:05.730
Our speaker from last
time, Michael Mauboussin

00:01:05.730 --> 00:01:10.290
spoke about the role of
luck and skill in life.

00:01:10.290 --> 00:01:12.280
He spoke about how
there is not often

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:16.120
a linear cause and effect
chain, but a spectrum

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:18.970
of probabilistic
outcomes in life.

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:21.990
Mohnish takes that
one step further.

00:01:21.990 --> 00:01:25.190
He talks about
being preferential

00:01:25.190 --> 00:01:27.540
towards probabilistic
scenarios where

00:01:27.540 --> 00:01:31.210
you have a limited downside,
but a disproportionately

00:01:31.210 --> 00:01:34.020
high upside.

00:01:34.020 --> 00:01:37.700
Also I could go on and on
about his investing philosophy,

00:01:37.700 --> 00:01:42.330
his philanthropic activities,
so on and so forth.

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:46.480
But I think what we'll
see here is how he really

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:48.770
cares about connecting
with the audience

00:01:48.770 --> 00:01:50.460
and how good of a teacher he is.

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:53.610
So without further ado,
ladies and gentlemen,

00:01:53.610 --> 00:01:55.450
please join me in
welcoming Mohnish Pabrai.

00:02:00.110 --> 00:02:01.432
MOHNISH PABRAI: Thank you.

00:02:01.432 --> 00:02:02.140
Thank you, Sarab.

00:02:02.140 --> 00:02:05.100
That's a wonderful warm welcome.

00:02:05.100 --> 00:02:06.680
Very much appreciated.

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:12.040
And it's pretty
exciting for me when

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:14.854
we got the e-mail from
Sarab about the possibility

00:02:14.854 --> 00:02:15.770
of speaking at Google.

00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:20.370
Because it's easy to be a fan.

00:02:20.370 --> 00:02:24.340
And I think it's a
wonderful company.

00:02:24.340 --> 00:02:28.850
In fact, I think in many ways
in the end, when we look back,

00:02:28.850 --> 00:02:33.890
I think Google might very well
be the greatest company ever

00:02:33.890 --> 00:02:37.800
created, for a
variety of reasons.

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:42.960
And one of your board
members-- he's not a friend,

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:44.680
he's an acquaintance of mine.

00:02:44.680 --> 00:02:47.230
And I'd asked him
a few years back,

00:02:47.230 --> 00:02:50.670
so what's the next Google?

00:02:50.670 --> 00:02:57.020
And his response, he instantly
said the next Google is Google.

00:02:57.020 --> 00:02:58.850
And I think that's
a great reply.

00:02:58.850 --> 00:03:03.530
Because I think that the way the
company is designed-- you know,

00:03:03.530 --> 00:03:09.050
Warren Buffett always says
that investing in businesses

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:14.790
with rapid change are the
enemy of the investor.

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:18.820
In many ways, Google is kind of
future-proof from that vantage

00:03:18.820 --> 00:03:21.090
point, just because of
the way it's structured.

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:25.890
And so it's quite exciting
to be outside the Plex

00:03:25.890 --> 00:03:28.880
and look in and see all
the great stuff going on.

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:31.410
So anyway, from a
number of perspectives,

00:03:31.410 --> 00:03:33.140
I'm delighted to be here.

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:38.660
And I'll always kick
myself for never

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:40.550
investing in Google stock.

00:03:40.550 --> 00:03:43.700
But there's still time, and we
might still get there one day,

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:46.320
so we'll see.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:49.140
So the Dhandho
investor, the book

00:03:49.140 --> 00:03:56.910
that came out a few years
back, Buffett has a quote.

00:03:56.910 --> 00:04:01.050
He says I'm a better investor,
because I'm a businessman.

00:04:01.050 --> 00:04:04.900
And I'm a better businessman,
because I'm an investor.

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:10.440
And in essence, that book,
the Dhandho investor,

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:17.300
is the expansion of that one
sentence into 100 plus pages,

00:04:17.300 --> 00:04:21.060
basically delving into
that particular nuance.

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:29.000
And the word Dhandho
is a Gujarati word.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.590
And do we have any
Gujaratis in the room?

00:04:31.590 --> 00:04:32.520
Oh, we have one.

00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:33.140
One Gujarati?

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:33.640
All right.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:34.240
That's good.

00:04:34.240 --> 00:04:40.270
So people always think
I'm from Gujarat in India,

00:04:40.270 --> 00:04:43.460
because I wrote a book
called the Dhandho Investor.

00:04:43.460 --> 00:04:46.660
And I have to always correct
them and say, I'm not Gujarati.

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:54.300
I had a roommate from
Gujarat, and he--

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:57.110
when I was doing my
undergraduate in engineering

00:04:57.110 --> 00:05:00.420
and he was also an engineering
major-- he used to disappear

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:02.720
on weekends, because
all his family,

00:05:02.720 --> 00:05:06.036
extended family, had all
these motels, and laundromats,

00:05:06.036 --> 00:05:07.660
and gas stations,
and whatnot that they

00:05:07.660 --> 00:05:09.460
owned in the Carolinas.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:12.310
And then he'd come
back on Sunday night,

00:05:12.310 --> 00:05:15.190
and he'd be bursting
with all these stories

00:05:15.190 --> 00:05:18.700
about the new investments
his family had made,

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:21.460
and all of the economics
of those investments.

00:05:21.460 --> 00:05:23.480
And then in the end,
he would finish and say

00:05:23.480 --> 00:05:25.400
Mohnish, Dhandho.

00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:30.450
And that was his way of saying
that-- the literal transition

00:05:30.450 --> 00:05:33.430
the word Dhandho means business.

00:05:33.430 --> 00:05:36.120
But the way the Gujaratis
use it, what it means

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:40.260
is, it's a way of doing
business where you basically

00:05:40.260 --> 00:05:45.770
have upside with almost
a nonexistent downside.

00:05:45.770 --> 00:05:47.580
Which is the key to investing.

00:05:47.580 --> 00:05:50.640
Like Buffet says, rule
number one, don't lose money.

00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:54.550
And rule number two, don't
forget rule number one.

00:05:54.550 --> 00:05:59.780
So that was kind of the backdrop
behind the title and the book.

00:05:59.780 --> 00:06:07.200
And Indians make up about 1%
of the population of the United

00:06:07.200 --> 00:06:08.170
States.

00:06:08.170 --> 00:06:09.870
A little over 3 million people.

00:06:09.870 --> 00:06:15.390
And the Patels, who
are from Gujarat

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:17.780
are a much smaller
portion of that 3 million.

00:06:17.780 --> 00:06:21.220
My guess is they would
probably be less than 1/5

00:06:21.220 --> 00:06:28.630
of 1% of the US population,
well under half a million or so.

00:06:28.630 --> 00:06:30.810
And even though
they're that small

00:06:30.810 --> 00:06:35.440
a portion, probably
more than 60%

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:40.040
of the motels in this country
are under Patel ownership.

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:44.080
And that's a stunning
statistic, considering

00:06:44.080 --> 00:06:47.870
that 40 years back there
were no Patels over here.

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:51.200
So they went from
basically a standing start

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:53.950
to pretty much
dominating this industry.

00:06:53.950 --> 00:06:55.310
And they've moved up markets.

00:06:55.310 --> 00:06:57.390
So they used to be
at the lowest end--

00:06:57.390 --> 00:07:01.200
the smallest 10, 20, 30
room type highway motels.

00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:05.472
And now, they're buying the
Marriott's and the Westerns

00:07:05.472 --> 00:07:06.680
and the Hiltons and all that.

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:09.270
So they're kind of
moving up the chain.

00:07:09.270 --> 00:07:15.780
And they came to the
United States as refugees,

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:19.990
and most of them came from
East Africa, from Uganda.

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:23.430
And at that time,
in the early '70s,

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:27.330
there was a dictator, Idi Amin,
who came into power in Uganda.

00:07:27.330 --> 00:07:32.480
And the Patels actually had
come to Uganda several decades,

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:34.390
more than 100
years, before that.

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:37.840
And they came mostly
as indentured laborers.

00:07:37.840 --> 00:07:41.610
But over time, using
their Dhandho techniques,

00:07:41.610 --> 00:07:44.350
they pretty much
controlled large portions

00:07:44.350 --> 00:07:46.420
of the Ugandan economy.

00:07:46.420 --> 00:07:49.890
And Idi Amin was very
pissed off about that.

00:07:49.890 --> 00:07:53.680
And his perspective was
that Africa is for Africans.

00:07:53.680 --> 00:07:58.400
And so what he did is he
pretty much nationalized

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:02.200
all their assets and took over
all their personal property

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:04.376
and threw them out
of the country.

00:08:04.376 --> 00:08:05.750
So there was
stateless, actually.

00:08:05.750 --> 00:08:09.290
They really had
no state to go to.

00:08:09.290 --> 00:08:12.870
India was reeling from
the Bangladesh war and all

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:14.370
the refugees coming
from Bangladesh.

00:08:14.370 --> 00:08:19.310
So India actually refused to
take the Patels in as refugees.

00:08:19.310 --> 00:08:21.640
England took some.

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.720
In the United States, at that
time, the Nixon administration,

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:26.560
they were quite
familiar with the issue.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:29.834
And they were sympathetic
to the plight of the Patels,

00:08:29.834 --> 00:08:30.750
but they were limited.

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:34.679
So the United States took
in a few thousand Patels.

00:08:34.679 --> 00:08:36.990
A few more thousand
came to Canada.

00:08:36.990 --> 00:08:40.929
And most of these Patels
who showed up in the US

00:08:40.929 --> 00:08:43.200
in the early '70s
didn't have that

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:45.210
much in the way of education.

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:47.810
And the only money they could
really carry with themselves

00:08:47.810 --> 00:08:51.090
were whatever they could
convert into gold quickly,

00:08:51.090 --> 00:08:53.720
a few thousand dollars.

00:08:53.720 --> 00:08:55.940
So that they landed up
in the United States.

00:08:55.940 --> 00:09:00.695
And they really found that they
had virtually no skills which

00:09:00.695 --> 00:09:02.510
were of use to most employers.

00:09:02.510 --> 00:09:07.100
They had a heavy
accent, and really

00:09:07.100 --> 00:09:10.490
didn't have much
in terms of skills.

00:09:10.490 --> 00:09:16.490
But they found that
motels, buying motels,

00:09:16.490 --> 00:09:18.700
was a great way to go.

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:23.230
And the reason they thought
that was because a typical Patel

00:09:23.230 --> 00:09:29.450
family, at the time, could buy
a 10 or 15 room motel for well

00:09:29.450 --> 00:09:32.840
under $100,000, maybe
$50,000 to $75,000.

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:36.900
And the family could live in
one or two of those rooms.

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:39.900
And because motel
are labor intensive,

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:42.260
they would pretty much
fire all the staff,

00:09:42.260 --> 00:09:45.250
and the family would
do all the work.

00:09:45.250 --> 00:09:47.720
So laundry, cleaning rooms,
watching the front desk.

00:09:47.720 --> 00:09:51.340
Everything was done by
different members of the family.

00:09:51.340 --> 00:09:55.470
And they became
low cost operators.

00:09:55.470 --> 00:09:58.820
They looked at every single
facet of the business.

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:02.850
And so once a motel came
under Patel ownership,

00:10:02.850 --> 00:10:03.770
two things happened.

00:10:03.770 --> 00:10:06.380
One is that the
operating cost dropped.

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:08.430
And because the operating
costs were lower,

00:10:08.430 --> 00:10:13.270
they were able to charge lower
rates and increase occupancy.

00:10:13.270 --> 00:10:15.820
And so typically,
the Patel owned

00:10:15.820 --> 00:10:20.040
motel in a particular area would
always do economically better,

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:23.520
in terms of cash flows, then the
other non-Patel owned motels.

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:25.880
And as soon as they
had enough cash flow,

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:28.830
they would buy the second
motel, and then the third motel.

00:10:28.830 --> 00:10:31.530
And they'd just keep levering
them and buying them up.

00:10:31.530 --> 00:10:35.250
And we end up with the
result of where we are today,

00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:40.180
where they pretty much
dominate the space.

00:10:40.180 --> 00:10:46.510
And that aspect to the way they
went about doing their business

00:10:46.510 --> 00:10:48.646
has a lot of correlation
with investing.

00:10:48.646 --> 00:10:50.020
Because the whole
Buffet sentence

00:10:50.020 --> 00:10:54.250
of being a good businessman
is a great skill

00:10:54.250 --> 00:10:56.300
set to be a great investor.

00:10:56.300 --> 00:10:59.790
And the particular
facet that they

00:10:59.790 --> 00:11:04.520
followed was this notion
that I call "heads I win,

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:06.440
and tails I don't lose much."

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:09.090
So if you looked at the
economics of a Patel

00:11:09.090 --> 00:11:12.130
buying a motel, typically they
would put $5,000 or $10,000

00:11:12.130 --> 00:11:13.120
down.

00:11:13.120 --> 00:11:15.970
And most of it was a bank loan.

00:11:15.970 --> 00:11:19.750
And if for some
reason they were not

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:23.220
able to manage the cash
flows, the banks really

00:11:23.220 --> 00:11:27.400
would prefer not to take the
motel back, foreclosing it.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:30.090
They would prefer or do
what they did recently

00:11:30.090 --> 00:11:32.900
in the financial crisis,
extend and pretend.

00:11:32.900 --> 00:11:38.300
Keep the same guy running it
and hope that things improve.

00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:41.210
So either way, the end
result was the Patels,

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:43.980
even with high leverage,
were unlikely to lose

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:44.690
their properties.

00:11:44.690 --> 00:11:45.356
And they didn't.

00:11:45.356 --> 00:11:47.860
Because they were
smart operators,

00:11:47.860 --> 00:11:49.930
they got nowhere near that mark.

00:11:49.930 --> 00:11:52.550
And after a few years,
the banks actually

00:11:52.550 --> 00:11:56.910
wanted to lend to motels
under Patel ownership,

00:11:56.910 --> 00:11:58.660
because they saw the
default rates and all

00:11:58.660 --> 00:12:01.390
that were markedly
different than the rest

00:12:01.390 --> 00:12:02.640
of the population.

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:05.920
And so that worked out
quite well for them.

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:14.350
And there's this
notion that it's just

00:12:14.350 --> 00:12:21.450
the Patels that have this
tight-fisted way of operating,

00:12:21.450 --> 00:12:23.650
and this "heads I win,
tails I don't lose much."

00:12:23.650 --> 00:12:27.820
But it actually
is available to us

00:12:27.820 --> 00:12:30.550
anywhere we look, and you find
it in all kinds of places.

00:12:30.550 --> 00:12:39.020
So for example, if you look at
Richard Branson in England, who

00:12:39.020 --> 00:12:41.780
is as far away from the
Patels as you could think of.

00:12:41.780 --> 00:12:44.490
And if you examine
the way Branson runs

00:12:44.490 --> 00:12:49.320
his different businesses,
they're very much in sync

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:53.110
with the Patel model
of operating with

00:12:53.110 --> 00:12:56.340
"heads I win, tails
I don't lose much."

00:12:56.340 --> 00:13:01.710
So for example, before the
formation of Virgin Atlantic

00:13:01.710 --> 00:13:04.390
airlines, Branson used to
be in the music business.

00:13:04.390 --> 00:13:06.640
He was a publisher of music.

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:12.750
And these different [INAUDIBLE]
like Boy George and the Sex

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:14.890
Pistols and so on were
some of the brands

00:13:14.890 --> 00:13:18.810
that he had brought up.

00:13:18.810 --> 00:13:22.370
So one day he goes
to his partners

00:13:22.370 --> 00:13:26.950
and says that he wants
to start an airline.

00:13:26.950 --> 00:13:31.550
And he wants to basically fly
between London and New York,

00:13:31.550 --> 00:13:36.120
and that he thinks it's a
great market to go into.

00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:37.830
So his partners
were quite floored.

00:13:37.830 --> 00:13:42.060
They said look, we're doing
very well in the music business.

00:13:42.060 --> 00:13:43.870
We know nothing about
the airline business.

00:13:43.870 --> 00:13:46.980
You need a jumbo jet to get
into the airline business.

00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:49.640
And that jumbo jet costs
about $200 million.

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:52.659
We don't have $200 million,
and we don't know anything

00:13:52.659 --> 00:13:53.450
about the business.

00:13:53.450 --> 00:13:56.090
So he says, well, someone
sent me this business plan.

00:13:56.090 --> 00:13:57.300
And Branson was smart.

00:13:57.300 --> 00:14:00.840
He said that if an executive
in the music business

00:14:00.840 --> 00:14:05.760
gets a business plan to start
an airline flying between London

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:08.470
and New York, you know
that this business plan has

00:14:08.470 --> 00:14:11.350
gone to 300 other
places before that,

00:14:11.350 --> 00:14:14.100
and got turned down at every
place that knew anything

00:14:14.100 --> 00:14:15.850
about the business.

00:14:15.850 --> 00:14:18.280
But he was intrigued
by the plan.

00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:23.110
And he tried calling British
Airways over the weekend

00:14:23.110 --> 00:14:24.510
to try to book
some flights, just

00:14:24.510 --> 00:14:26.805
to see what the customer
service was like.

00:14:26.805 --> 00:14:28.240
And he couldn't get through.

00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:31.390
So he said, well either
there's so much business

00:14:31.390 --> 00:14:34.580
that there's enough there for
a second player to come in.

00:14:34.580 --> 00:14:38.477
Or they're so bad
that a second player

00:14:38.477 --> 00:14:39.810
can come in and do a better job.

00:14:39.810 --> 00:14:42.220
Either way, there's
room for that.

00:14:42.220 --> 00:14:45.570
And then his partners told
him that, yeah, that's

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:47.140
all fine Richard.

00:14:47.140 --> 00:14:48.740
But we don't have the money.

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:49.810
We don't have the jet.

00:14:49.810 --> 00:14:50.720
We don't have a jumbo jet.

00:14:50.720 --> 00:14:51.886
How are we going to do this?

00:14:51.886 --> 00:14:57.760
And so what he did is, he
called (206)-555-1212--

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:01.310
which is the
operator in Seattle--

00:15:01.310 --> 00:15:03.090
to get the number for Boeing.

00:15:03.090 --> 00:15:06.910
And they gave him the
Boeing main phone number.

00:15:06.910 --> 00:15:08.940
And he called
Boeing, and he said

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:13.560
he wanted to speak to someone
who leases jumbo jets.

00:15:13.560 --> 00:15:16.370
And they'd repeatedly
hang up on him.

00:15:16.370 --> 00:15:19.754
And finally, he
got to some guy who

00:15:19.754 --> 00:15:20.920
would actually speak to him.

00:15:20.920 --> 00:15:23.880
And he said, look, we typically
have one or two customers

00:15:23.880 --> 00:15:25.430
in each country.

00:15:25.430 --> 00:15:27.820
We know who they are.

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:30.436
You're not one of the people
we talk to in England, goodbye.

00:15:30.436 --> 00:15:31.060
So he said, no.

00:15:31.060 --> 00:15:31.560
No, listen.

00:15:31.560 --> 00:15:36.650
Before you hang up, do you
have an old, used jumbo

00:15:36.650 --> 00:15:40.130
that you'd lease to one of these
customers if they came to you.

00:15:40.130 --> 00:15:41.770
He said, well, you're
not one of them.

00:15:41.770 --> 00:15:43.510
But yeah, if they came
to us, we actually

00:15:43.510 --> 00:15:45.050
do have an old
jumbo lying around.

00:15:45.050 --> 00:15:47.400
He said, oh, well if these
people came to you, what

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:50.240
would it cost to
release the jumbo?

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:53.160
And so the guy mentioned
the pricing and such.

00:15:53.160 --> 00:15:55.160
He said, would you do
a short term lease,

00:15:55.160 --> 00:15:57.180
because the jumbo is
just sitting there.

00:15:57.180 --> 00:15:59.800
He said, yeah, we'd be
flexible with our customers.

00:15:59.800 --> 00:16:03.765
So he convinced Boeing
to lease him that jumbo.

00:16:03.765 --> 00:16:06.370
Because it was
just sitting there.

00:16:06.370 --> 00:16:09.830
And then, in the
airline business,

00:16:09.830 --> 00:16:12.640
before the plane takes off,
you've sold all the tickets.

00:16:12.640 --> 00:16:16.650
So your revenue comes in
before you've spent a dime.

00:16:16.650 --> 00:16:18.790
And then you pay
for the fuel 30 days

00:16:18.790 --> 00:16:20.380
after the plane has landed.

00:16:20.380 --> 00:16:23.990
So it's a negative
flow business,

00:16:23.990 --> 00:16:27.320
in the sense that you don't
need even working capital.

00:16:27.320 --> 00:16:30.170
And so he went
about advertising,

00:16:30.170 --> 00:16:36.750
and got the staff hired,
and got everything going,

00:16:36.750 --> 00:16:39.250
and got this airline
off the ground.

00:16:39.250 --> 00:16:42.900
And if you think
about it, if someone

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:48.780
can start a business in a
tightly regulated industry

00:16:48.780 --> 00:16:53.120
like aviation, with
very high Capex needs,

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:57.910
like needing these
jumbos, with no capital,

00:16:57.910 --> 00:17:00.550
then you can pretty much say
you can do that in any business.

00:17:00.550 --> 00:17:01.280
Right?

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:04.569
And if you think about
the way Branson set it up,

00:17:04.569 --> 00:17:06.470
he had no downside.

00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:10.660
Because what would happen
if the thing didn't work?

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:12.520
Well he'd just
return the airplane.

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:14.400
And it'd be a few
thousand dollars

00:17:14.400 --> 00:17:16.339
in terms of tens of
thousands or whatever.

00:17:16.339 --> 00:17:18.380
And his music
business at that time

00:17:18.380 --> 00:17:23.084
was producing about $3 or $4
million a year in cash flows.

00:17:23.084 --> 00:17:24.500
So they had more
than enough money

00:17:24.500 --> 00:17:27.500
to take care of
any eventualities.

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:30.530
And that's the
nature of Dhandho is

00:17:30.530 --> 00:17:33.920
that you're making
these asymmetric bets.

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:35.680
And one of the
reasons why I think

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:40.130
Google is such a fascinating
and incredible place-- because I

00:17:40.130 --> 00:17:43.130
don't think Sergey
and Larry ever

00:17:43.130 --> 00:17:44.850
thought about it
in these terms--

00:17:44.850 --> 00:17:48.595
but Google is the
ultimate, Dhandho business.

00:17:48.595 --> 00:17:50.720
And the reason it's the
ultimate Dhandho businesses

00:17:50.720 --> 00:17:54.470
is if you look at, for example,
your self-driving cars.

00:17:54.470 --> 00:17:58.016
So the self-driving cars,
the real Capex on that

00:17:58.016 --> 00:17:59.890
would come when you need
to build large scale

00:17:59.890 --> 00:18:02.430
factories to produce
millions of cars.

00:18:02.430 --> 00:18:04.700
It is not when you're doing
the R&amp;D for those cars,

00:18:04.700 --> 00:18:07.240
or have a few
prototypes, and put

00:18:07.240 --> 00:18:09.670
a few dozen engineers on
it, and that sort of thing.

00:18:09.670 --> 00:18:12.850
So if you think of the
outflows or outlays Google

00:18:12.850 --> 00:18:15.900
has on the self-driven
car, I would

00:18:15.900 --> 00:18:18.770
bet you're probably spending
more on food on the campus

00:18:18.770 --> 00:18:21.240
then you're spending on
the self-driven cars.

00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:22.990
And so it's an asymmetric bet.

00:18:22.990 --> 00:18:23.490
Right?

00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:27.050
It's basically if it doesn't
work, it has no impact.

00:18:27.050 --> 00:18:29.350
No impact on cash
flows or anything.

00:18:29.350 --> 00:18:31.300
And if it does work,
it's game changing.

00:18:31.300 --> 00:18:32.300
Same thing with Android.

00:18:32.300 --> 00:18:34.050
You know, a few
years back, Android

00:18:34.050 --> 00:18:37.020
with a project like
the self-driven car is.

00:18:37.020 --> 00:18:41.810
And it moved from being one
of those outlier projects

00:18:41.810 --> 00:18:43.670
to very much central
and cash flow.

00:18:43.670 --> 00:18:47.960
And then, even when you
look at your balloons

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:53.660
with the internet access, or
all the different other projects

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:57.240
that you guys are working on
it, basically each one of those

00:18:57.240 --> 00:19:00.730
has the potential to
be a game changer,

00:19:00.730 --> 00:19:04.410
in terms of where
the world ends up.

00:19:04.410 --> 00:19:11.090
But none of those have
costs associated with them

00:19:11.090 --> 00:19:14.340
that have anything
to do with how

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:16.190
threatening the
company in any way.

00:19:16.190 --> 00:19:16.690
Right?

00:19:16.690 --> 00:19:19.877
I mean it's a rounding error
in terms of the cash flows

00:19:19.877 --> 00:19:20.960
that the company produces.

00:19:20.960 --> 00:19:26.620
So the fact that the DNA
of a place like Google

00:19:26.620 --> 00:19:32.720
is able to do things which
are not in adjacent fields,

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:34.160
it's quite spectacular.

00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:37.224
And most other companies
don't have the DNA

00:19:37.224 --> 00:19:38.140
to be able to do that.

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:40.980
And my two cents
looking from the outside

00:19:40.980 --> 00:19:43.340
is, probably the
only other business

00:19:43.340 --> 00:19:47.730
I see that has the ability
to do that is Amazon.

00:19:47.730 --> 00:19:51.000
And I think in the end, you
will meet them head to head

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.660
on a number of different fronts.

00:19:53.660 --> 00:19:56.160
So that's why it's
a great place to be.

00:19:58.920 --> 00:20:02.590
And the other notion I just
wanted of talk briefly about

00:20:02.590 --> 00:20:05.900
is this notion of compounding.

00:20:05.900 --> 00:20:08.537
So can we play that video?

00:20:08.537 --> 00:20:10.870
We'll just play maybe a couple
of minutes of this video,

00:20:10.870 --> 00:20:13.136
and then I'll just
talk about it.

00:20:13.136 --> 00:20:14.132
